covid_cases <- read_rds(here::here("data", "covid_cases.rds"))

Visualisation of the CovidCases dataframe

First, we will display the amount of covid cases per state on the USA map:

grouped_by <- covid_cases%>%
  group_by(State)%>% 
  summarise(amount_of_covid_cases = round(sum(Daily_new_cases),3))

colnames(grouped_by)[1]<-"state"

plot_usmap(data = grouped_by, values = "amount_of_covid_cases", color = "red") + 
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "white", high= "red",name = "Amount of cases", label = scales::comma) + 
  theme(legend.position = "right") + theme(legend.position = "right") +
     labs(title = "USA map that represents the amount of covid cases", subtitle = "For each state")

We can see that the state with the highest amount of covid cases is California, this insight makes sense since California is the the most populous country in the United States. Other countries that stand out in the map in terms of amount of covid cases are Texas, Florida and New-York.

# Data preperations for the first plot

# Comupute the total amount of new cases per each date and region in the USA
cases_per_date_region <- covid_cases%>%
  group_by(Date, Region)%>% 
    summarise(Sum_of_cases = sum(Daily_new_cases),.groups='drop')

# Comupute the accumulate amount of new cases grouped by region 
summed_cases <- cases_per_date_region%>%
  group_by(Region)%>%
  mutate(cumulative_cases = cumsum(Sum_of_cases))

Now, lets visualize the amount of new covid cases over time for each region:

# First plot - The amount of covid cases according over time

ggplot(summed_cases, aes(x = Date, y = cumulative_cases, color = as.factor(Region))) +
  geom_line(size = 1)+
    scale_color_brewer(palette="Paired")+
   labs(title = "Amount of covid cases over time",subtitle="By Region", x= "Date", y = "Amount of covid cases" ,color = "Region")

This plot describes the cumulative amount of new cases by regions. When the slope of the line is extreme it might indicate a wave of illness. For example, around July 2020 we can see an extreme change in the slope of the South line and from this we can conclude that from this point of time the morbidity has pounced. In addition to that, we can see that the South, as we mentioned before, is the region with the highest amount of new cases per a day and it achieves the highest amount of total new cases.

Now, lets explore the histogram of new cases over time separated by the different regions:

# Second plot - The amount of new cases over time by region

# Create a copy for covid_cases dataset including only positive values for the column "Daily_new_cases"

copy_covid_cases<-covid_cases%>%filter(Daily_new_cases>=0)

# Create the plot
ggplot(data = copy_covid_cases, aes(x = Date, y = Daily_new_cases, fill = as.factor(Region))) +
  geom_bar(alpha = 0.7, stat="identity")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45,hjust=1)) +
  facet_wrap(~Region, scales = "free")+
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("gold", "gold3", "lightgoldenrod2", "goldenrod2", "darkgoldenrod1", "darkgoldenrod4"))+
   labs(title = "Amount of new cases per day over time", subtitle = "By Region", x= "Date", y = "Amount of new cases per day",fill = "Region")

This plot describes the different distribution of new covid cases per day during the time for each one of the regions. We can notice that the distributions that reach high values of new cases per day are the distributions of the midwest and south, which enforces the early observations from the previous plot.

# Fourth plot -  The average amount of new cases per a day in the South region

# Compute the average deaths for each state in the South Region in a descending order 
south_filtered <- covid_cases%>%
  filter(Region == "South")%>%
  group_by(State)%>% 
  summarise(Average_cases = round(mean(Daily_new_cases),3))

# Create the plot 
ggplot(south_filtered, aes(x = reorder(State,-Average_cases), y = Average_cases, fill = as.factor(State)))+
  geom_bar(alpha = 0.5, stat ="identity", color = "black")+
   labs(title = "Average amount of new cases per day according to state", subtitle = "In the South Region", x= "State", y = "Average amount of new cases per day",fill = "State")

We can see that the states Texas and Florida are the states with the highest amount of average covid cases in the South Region. This insight makes sense since Texas is the seccond most populated country in the USA and Florida is the third most populated country in the USA.

Visualisation of the sum_cases dataframe

First, lets explore the relationship between the amount of active cases and the amount of recovery cases from covid:

# First plot - connection between the amount of active patients to the amount of recovered patients
filtered_sum_cases <- sum_cases %>% filter(Daily_recovered<=300000)

# Create the plot 
ggplot(filtered_sum_cases,
mapping = aes(x = Active, y = Daily_recovered)) +
geom_point()+
geom_smooth()+
labs(title = "Relationship between the amount of active and recovery cases",  x = "Amount of active cases", y = "Amount of recovery cases")

We can see that there is a connection between the amount of active patients to the amount of recovered patients - as the number of active patients in a day increases, so does the number of people recovering from the disease. A possible explanation for this evidence is that usually it takes 2 weeks on average to recover from covid. Therefore, it makes sense that the amount of active patients and the amount of recovered patients are proportional.

# Calculate the total amount of active cases and the total amount of new cases per month and year

group_by_monthyear <- seperated_date_sum_cases %>% 
  group_by(month_and_year) %>% summarise(
    ActivesAmount = sum(Active), DeathCasesAmount = sum(Daily_deaths))

# Create a pivoted dataframe 
pivoted_monthyear <- group_by_monthyear%>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("ActivesAmount", "DeathCasesAmount") , names_to = "active_or_death", values_to = "amount")

Now, lets visualize the total amount of active and death cases for each month over time

# Seccond plot - Amount of new covid cases and death cases over time

# Create the plot 
ggplot(data = pivoted_monthyear, aes(x = month_and_year, y=amount, fill = as.factor(active_or_death))) +
  geom_bar(alpha = 0.7,stat="identity", color = "black")+
  facet_wrap(~active_or_death,nrow=2, scales = "free") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("#FF9966", "#CC3300")) +
   theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45,hjust=1)) +
    #scale_x_discrete(guide = guide_axis(check.overlap = TRUE)) +
   labs(title = "Amount of active cases and death cases", subtitle = "According to each month" , x= "Date", y =        "Amount of active cases or death cases",fill = "Actives/Death cases")

This plot can describe the spread and the progress of the covid disease: It can be seen that in the beginning of the covid disease (around March 2020) an increase has began in the number of active patients: The number of active patients per month increases from month to month and receives its peek at January 2021 - as we saw earlier this is the month with the highest amount of average active cases. After January 2021 we can see a descent trend in the number of active cases per month, until May 2021. We can assume that this descent trend is a result of the immunization policy or a result of people awareness of the disease.

In addition to that, we can see that the death cases appeared in March 2020 and their amount increased significantly in April 2020. From April 2020 to November 2020 we can see that the amount of death cases per month stayed quite stable and then in December 2021 there was a marked increase in the amount of death cases and it peeks in January 2021. After January 2021 there is a decrease in the amount of monthly death cases.

Another interesting insight is that there is a correspondence between the advance of the amount of active cases and the amount of death cases per a month: For example, both of them receives their peek in January 2021 and then there is a descent in both of them. This also makes sense, when the amount of active cases increase we except to see as a result a growth in the number of death cases and same in the opposite direction.

Lets visualize the amount of daily new confirmed and recovered patients over time:

# Third plot - The amount of new covid and recovery cases over time

filtered<- filter(sum_cases, Daily_recovered<=300000)

colors <- c("Confirmed" = "#ff9933", "Recovered" = "#0066cc")

# Create the plot 
ggplot(data = filtered, mapping = aes(x=Date)) +
  geom_point(aes(y=Daily_confirmed,color="Confirmed"))+
  geom_point(aes(y=Daily_recovered,color="Recovered"))+
   labs(title = "The amount of daily new and recovery cases over time", x= "Date", y = "Amount of recovery/new cases",color = "Confirmed/Recovered")

We can see a general trend of increase in the number of confirmed patients and recovered patients over time until January 2021. After January 2021 there is a decline in the amount of new confirmed patients and the recovered patients. As we expected, we can see that the amount of new confirmed cases and the amount of recovered patients increase and decrease together respectively and this insight reinforces the conclusion from the first plot. In addition to that, at the begining of the epidemic we can see 2 relatively small waves, and then towards December 2020 it can be seen that there is a large wave that has reached its peak in January 2021. As we expected, we can see that the amount of new confirmed cases and the amount of recovered patients increase and decrease together respectively.
